1. Problem
  -> In microservices or large-scale applications, repeatedly hitting the database for the same data
     increases latency and database load.
  -> To reduce response time and improive scalability, we use caching.

2. what cache actually does 
  -> Cache store frequently accessed data temporarily in memory so future request can 
     be served without querying the database again.

3. Request flow
   ->   Client Request --> Controller --> Service Layer --> Check Cache 
                                         Return Data <--  Hit <--||--> Miss -> DB Call --> Save In Cache -->  return Response
   -> On the first request, data comes from the database and gets stored in cache.
      Subsequent requests directly return from cache, which reduces DB calls.

4. Spring Bot Cache Flow
    -> Step 1:- Enable Cache 

       @EnableCaching
        @SpringBootApplication
        public class App {
        }

       Write @EnableChaching on top of @SpringBootApplication
       This activates Spring's cache management mechanism.


    -> Step 2:- Use @Cacheable

       @Cacheable(value = "users", Id="")
       public User getUser(Long id) {
            return userRepository.findById(id).orElseThrow();
       }
       Before executing the method, Spring checks whether data with key id exists in cache.
       If present, method execution is skipped and cached data is returned.
       Otherwise, Spring executes the method, stores result in cache, and returns response.

5. Cache Key
   -> Every cached entry is stored using a unique cache key.
   -> Wrong cache key design can cause stale data or duplicate cache entries.

6. Cache Eviction
   -> Caching improves performance, but stale data becomes a major challenge.
   -> So whenever data changes, cache must be updated or removed.

      @CacheEvict(value="", id="")
      public void deleteUser(Long id){
        repository.deleteById(id);
      }
   -> When user data changes or gets deleted, corresponding cache 
      entry must be remoed to maintain consistency.

7. @CachePut
    -> @CachePut always executes the method and update cache with latest value.
      Unlike @Cacheable, it does not skip method execution.

     @CachePut(value = "", key = "")
     public User update(User user){
         return repository.save(user);
      }

8. Type of Cache
    -> Local Cache
        ex: - 1) ConcurrentHashMap
              2) Caffeine
      Stored inside application memory. Fast but no shared across microservice instances.

    -> Distributed Cache 
       ex:- 1) redis 
            2) Hazelcast
        In microservices, distributed cache like redis is preferred because all service instances
        share the same cache.

9. Why Redis is popular
   Redis is widely used because it is in-memory, extremely fast, supports TTL, distributed caching, pub-sub, and persistence.

10. TTL
    TTL = Time TO Live
    Cache should expire after some duration to avoid stale data.

11. Real Project Usage 
    -> In my project, we cached frequently accessed master data like user profile,
       configuration data, and dashboard statistics using Redis.
       This reduced repeated DB queries and improved API response time significantly.

12. Problems in caching
    -> Common Challenges
       
        Cache Stampede
        Multiple requests hit DB when cache expires simultaneously.

        Stale Data
        Cache contains old data after DB update.

        Memory Overflow 
        Too much caching can increase memory usage.

        Cache Synchronization
        Multiple microservice instances may hold inconsistent cache.

13. When not to use cache

    Highly dynamic or constantly changing data is usually not good for caching because cache invalidation
    overhead becomes high.



Short answer 
“Caching is used to reduce database load and improve API response time by storing frequently accessed data temporarily in memory.
In Spring Boot, we enable caching using @EnableCaching and cache method results using @Cacheable.
When a request comes, Spring first checks cache. If data exists, it returns directly without executing the method. Otherwise it fetches from DB and stores result in cache.
For consistency, we use @CacheEvict to remove stale cache and @CachePut to update cache.
In microservices, Redis is commonly used as distributed cache because multiple instances can share cached data.”
    
  
